\begin_layout Section
Properties of Semiconductors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that the conductivity of semiconductors is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma=ne\mu+pe\mu\label{eq:conductivity}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the number of electrons, 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 is the electronic charge, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is the mobility in 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{{cm}}^{2}/\text{{V}/\text{{s}}}$
\end_inset

.
 The following trends for conductivity versus temperature are noted for
 metals, semiconductors, and insulators:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Metals: 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 are constant with temperature.
 Mobility is related to temperature as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\propto T^{-a}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is temperature and 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a constant.
 Conductivity decreases with increasing temperature.
 The resistivity 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\rho=1/\sigma\right)$
\end_inset

 can be written as a sum of contributing factors using Matthiessen's rule
 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho=\rho_{0}+\rho(T)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{0}$
\end_inset

 is a constant and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(T)$
\end_inset

 is the temperature dependent resistivity.
 A typical carrier concentration for a metal is 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{23}\text{{cm}}^{-3}$
\end_inset

.
 Metals do not have a gap between the conduction and valence bands.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Semiconductors: 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 are not constant with temperature but are thermally activated.
 Mobility is related to temperature as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\propto T^{-a}$
\end_inset

.
 The typical range of carrier concentrations for semiconductors is 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{14}-10^{20}\text{{cm}}^{-3}$
\end_inset

.
 The range of bandgaps for semiconductors is typically 
\begin_inset Formula $0.1-3.0\text{\,{eV}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Insulators: 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 are much lower than they are in metals and semiconductors.
 A typical carrier concentration for an insulator is 
\begin_inset Formula $<10^{7}\text{{cm}}^{-3}$
\end_inset

.
 The conductivity is generally a function of temperature.
 The bandgap for insulators is 
\begin_inset Formula $>3.0\,\text{{eV}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Law of Mass Action
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equilibrium concentration of electrons and holes can be determined by
 treating them as chemical species.
 At equilibrium,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
[np]\rightleftharpoons[n]+[p]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rate constant is given by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{{[n][p]}}{[np]}=K(T)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
K(T)=[F(T)]^{2}\exp[-\Delta E/kT]
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Consider the intrinsic case, that is, when the semiconductor is not doped
 with chemical impurities.
 For this case,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
[n]=[p]=[n_{i}]=A\exp[-\Delta E/2kT]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the intrinsic carrier concentration.
 For an intrinsic semiconductor, the conductivity is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma=2n_{i}e\mu\cong\sigma_{0}\exp[-\Delta E/2kT]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

